                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Fourth, nasal povidone-iodine is formulated to prevent nasal irritation.14 Nasal povidone-iodine is thickened, and pH balanced, to be nonirritating, to have a sustained effect, and to address the physiology of the nose.14 We observed no issues with sneezing or coughing induced by nasal povidone-iodine14 in our randomized trial.6 The product14 was well tolerated and without adverse events. The authors are unaware of reports suggesting otherwise.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 72,
                    "end": 74,
                    "mention": "14",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                },
                {
                    "start": 219,
                    "end": 221,
                    "mention": "14",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                },
                {
                    "start": 302,
                    "end": 304,
                    "mention": "14",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                },
                {
                    "start": 329,
                    "end": 330,
                    "mention": "6",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF11"
                },
                {
                    "start": 342,
                    "end": 344,
                    "mention": "14",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Fifth, the authors are unaware of evidence suggesting that chlorhexidine gluconate 0.12% oral rinse is associated with inducing cough. This hypothetical concern raised by Dr Maguire1 should be balanced against the substantial evidence that the oral reservoir contains a high viral load that should be attenuated to prevent the spread of COVID-19 and that 0.12% chlorhexidine gluconate may be useful in achieving this goal.7\u20139 Whether the alternative of povidone-iodine oral rinse is more effective is currently unknown.7,8,11,12,15",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 181,
                    "end": 182,
                    "mention": "1",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                },
                {
                    "start": 422,
